post_cb({"15508148": {"CommentCount": "4", "AcceptedAnswerId": "15508173", "ClosedDate": "2013-03-19T19:01:19.517", "CreationDate": "2013-03-19T18:56:07.747", "LastActivityDate": "2013-03-19T18:57:32.043", "PostTypeId": "1", "ViewCount": "7311", "FavoriteCount": "3", "Title": "What is the type of a string literal in C++?", "Id": "15508148", "Score": "8", "Body": "<p>For example, what is the type of the string literal \"Hello\", <code>const char[6]</code> or <code>const char*</code> ?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><string><types>", "OwnerUserId": "1042389", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "15508172": {"ParentId": "15508148", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>The Standard defines it as an \"array of n <code>const char</code>\", so it's <code>const char[n]</code> (n is the size of the string, including the terminating NUL byte).</p>\n<p>Section 7, \u00a7 2.14.15:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_15508148_15508172_0\">A narrow string literal has type \u201carray of n const char\u201d, where n is the size of the string as defined below, and has static storage duration.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "Id": "15508172", "PostTypeId": "2", "OwnerDisplayName": "user529758", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2013-03-19T18:57:30.777", "LastActivityDate": "2013-03-19T18:57:30.777"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_15508148_15508172_0": {"section_id": 5356, "quality": 1.0, "length": 15}, "so_15508148_15508173_0": {"section_id": 5356, "quality": 1.0, "length": 21}}, "n3337": {"so_15508148_15508172_0": {"section_id": 5153, "quality": 1.0, "length": 15}, "so_15508148_15508173_0": {"section_id": 5153, "quality": 1.0, "length": 21}}, "n4659": {"so_15508148_15508172_0": {"section_id": 6781, "quality": 1.0, "length": 15}, "so_15508148_15508173_0": {"section_id": 6781, "quality": 1.0, "length": 21}}}, "15508173": {"ParentId": "15508148", "CommentCount": "10", "Body": "<p>The type of the string literal <code>\"Hello\"</code> is \"array of 6 <code>const</code> <code>char</code>\".</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_15508148_15508173_0\">Ordinary string literals and UTF-8 string literals are also referred to as narrow string literals. A narrow string literal has type \u201carray of <em>n</em> <code>const char</code>\u201d, where <em>n</em> is the size of the string [...]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It can, however, be converted to a <code>const char*</code> by array-to-pointer conversion. Array-to-pointer conversion results in a pointer to the first element of the array.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "150634", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "15508173", "Score": "14", "CreationDate": "2013-03-19T18:57:32.043", "LastActivityDate": "2013-03-19T18:57:32.043"}});